article.headline: Portland 77, Boise State 72
article.story: BOISE, Idaho (AP) -- Guard Eugene Jeter hit four crucial free throws in the final 8.5 seconds and scored a game-high 24 points to lead Portland to a 77-72 victory over Boise State on Sunday. Jeter's free throws, two with one-second to play, broke Boise State's (8-2) five-game winning streak, and revenged an earlier loss this season to the Broncos at Portland. Also helping Portland (6-5) were Casey Frandsen with 14, Dustin Geddis with 13 and Patrick Galos with 10. After Bryan Defares pulled the Broncos to within 73-72 with less than 10 seconds left, Jeter hit two free throws after being fouled on an inbound pass. He added two more free throws with one-second left after the Broncos missed a field-goal attempt and the Pilots rebounded and were fouled. Earlier the Broncos had pulled to a 66-66 tie with 4:24 remaining after Booker Nabors came off the bench to score 10 successive Bronco points. Jeter put Portland ahead 69-66 with a 3-point field goal with 3:51 remaining. The teams traded baskets until Defares drove for the uncontested lay-up to make it 73-72. Boise State was led by Nabors with 15 points and Jason Ellis and Defares each had 10. Ellis had 15 rebounds. Portland took advantage of 25 percent shooting by the Broncos to build a 33-19 lead with 3:10 left in the first half. But Franco Harris came off the bench in the final three minutes to score eight points to help bring the Broncos back to within four at the half, 38-34.
